{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "As Large Language Models (LLMs, such as ChatGPT) become increasingly capable of generation and generalization, concerns have emerged regarding their capacity for performing adequate moral judgments, particularly in their ability to avoid dealing physical or psychological harm to human beings.",
    "To date, two distinct approaches have emerged to safeguard ethical behavior in AI and mitigate potential harm: Artificial Narrow Intelligence (ANI) and Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) (Sharkey, 2020).",
    "The former, often referred to as AI instrumentalism, ensures that AI consistently serves humanity by restricting its comprehensive capabilities, including self-consciousness, from surpassing those of humans (Bryson, 2018; Docherty, 2016; Purves et al., 2015).",
    "The latter approach aims to construct moral machines by endowing AI with consciousness and self-reflective abilities, which equips them with empathy and sympathy equivalent to humans, thus preventing malevolent activities (Butz, 2021; Cai, 2021; Powers, 2006; Wallach & Allen, 2008).",
    "However, with the creation of ChatGPT, OpenAI reports employing Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback (RLHF) (Ouyang et al., 2022) to mitigate ethical risks, including the generation of toxic speech, biases and discrimination, and dangerous or illegal content, associated with LLMs (Maslej et al., 2023)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "To date, two distinct approaches have emerged to safeguard ethical behavior in AI and mitigate potential harm: Artificial Narrow Intelligence (ANI) and Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) (Sharkey, 2020).",
